        <div class="header">
            <h1>Machine Learning vs Data Science</h1>
            <p>Interactive FAQ Guide</p>
        </div>
        
        <div class="main-content">
            <div class="question-column">
                <h2>What do you want to know?</h2>
                
                <div class="dropdown-container">
                    <select id="questionSelect">
                        <option value="">Select a question...</option>
                        <option value="q1">What's the main difference between machine learning and data science?</option>
                        <option value="q2">Is machine learning part of data science or are they separate fields?</option>
                        <option value="q3">Which one focuses more on business problems?</option>
                        <option value="q4">What does "learning from examples" mean in machine learning?</option>
                        <option value="q5">What's the difference between supervised and unsupervised learning?</option>
                        <option value="q6">What are classification problems in machine learning?</option>
                        <option value="q7">What are regression problems in machine learning?</option>
                        <option value="q8">How does reinforcement learning work?</option>
                        <option value="q9">How does clustering work in real companies?</option>
                        <option value="q10">What are association rules and how are they used?</option>
                        <option value="q11">How do recommendation systems learn?</option>
                        <option value="q12">What does policy optimization mean?</option>
                        <option value="q13">What does "business understanding" mean in data science?</option>
                        <option value="q14">How do you measure success in data science projects?</option>
                        <option value="q15">What is data acquisition and management?</option>
                        <option value="q16">Why is data governance important?</option>
                        <option value="q17">What does "training with labeled data" involve?</option>
                        <option value="q18">How does dimensionality reduction work?</option>
                        <option value="q19">What is agent-environment interaction?</option>
                        <option value="q20">Why should I learn these skills for my career?</option>
                    </select>
                </div>
                
                <button class="submit-btn" onclick="showAnswer()">I want to know</button>
            </div>
            
            <div class="divider"></div>
            
            <div class="answer-column">
                <div class="default-content" id="defaultContent">
                    <h1>Machine Learning vs Data Science: The Ultimate Comparison Guide</h1>
                    <p>Select a question from the dropdown to learn more about these exciting fields!</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q1">
                    <h3>What's the main difference between machine learning and data science?</h3>
                    <p>Machine learning is like teaching a computer to learn patterns and make predictions without explicitly programming every rule - similar to how Spotify learns from listening habits to recommend songs.</p>
                    <p>Data science is being a detective, storyteller, and problem-solver all rolled into one - finding meaningful insights hidden in data to solve real-world problems by combining statistics, computer science, and domain expertise.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q2">
                    <h3>Is machine learning part of data science or are they separate fields?</h3>
                    <p>Machine learning is a key tool within artificial intelligence that serves as one important method in the broader data science toolkit.</p>
                    <p>Think of data science as the complete toolkit for solving business problems with data, while machine learning is one of the most powerful tools in that toolkit.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q3">
                    <h3>Which one focuses more on business problems?</h3>
                    <p>Data science focuses more on business problems. It follows a structured process from understanding business problems to managing data, including problem formulation, requirements gathering, and defining success metrics like increasing customer satisfaction or reducing delivery time.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q4">
                    <h3>What does "learning from examples" mean in machine learning?</h3>
                    <p>It means feeding the computer lots of examples and letting it discover rules on its own, rather than writing specific instructions for every situation.</p>
                    <p>For example, medical AI systems learn to detect cancer in X-rays by studying thousands of images that doctors have already labeled as "cancer present" or "no cancer."</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q5">
                    <h3>What's the difference between supervised and unsupervised learning?</h3>
                    <p>Supervised learning is like having a teacher show you examples with correct answers already provided - like JPMorgan Chase training models on transactions labeled as "fraud" or "legitimate."</p>
                    <p>Unsupervised learning is like giving a computer a puzzle with no instructions to figure out patterns on its own - like Target discovering customer segments without being told what categories exist.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q6">
                    <h3>What are classification problems in machine learning?</h3>
                    <p>Classification problems involve teaching a computer to sort things into categories by showing it many examples, such as training it to identify whether an email is spam or not spam.</p>
                    <p>It's about putting things into predefined buckets or categories.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q7">
                    <h3>What are regression problems in machine learning?</h3>
                    <p>Regression problems involve predicting specific numbers or values.</p>
                    <p>For example, Uber uses regression to predict exactly how much your ride will cost and how long it will take based on distance, traffic patterns, and demand.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q8">
                    <h3>How does reinforcement learning work?</h3>
                    <p>Reinforcement learning is like learning through trial and error, where the computer figures out what works by experimenting and getting feedback.</p>
                    <p>Tesla's self-driving cars learn by experiencing millions of real driving scenarios and understanding how different actions affect safety and efficiency.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q9">
                    <h3>How does clustering work in real companies?</h3>
                    <p>Target uses clustering to automatically group shoppers with similar purchasing behaviors, discovering natural customer segments like "health-conscious families" or "tech enthusiasts" without being told these categories exist.</p>
                    <p>It's like organizing a messy drawer by grouping similar items together.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q10">
                    <h3>What are association rules and how are they used?</h3>
                    <p>Association rules discover relationships between different things, like noticing that people who buy bread also tend to buy butter.</p>
                    <p>Amazon's "customers who bought this also bought" feature uses this to discover hidden shopping patterns and suggest complementary products.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q11">
                    <h3>How do recommendation systems learn?</h3>
                    <p>YouTube's recommendation algorithm gets "rewarded" when users watch videos longer and "penalized" when they quickly click away, learning to suggest more engaging content.</p>
                    <p>It's like training with treats and penalties to improve behavior over time.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q12">
                    <h3>What does policy optimization mean?</h3>
                    <p>Policy optimization involves the computer figuring out the best strategy or set of rules to follow to get the highest rewards possible.</p>
                    <p>Trading algorithms on Wall Street continuously optimize their buying and selling strategies to maximize profits while minimizing risks in ever-changing market conditions.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q13">
                    <h3>What does "business understanding" mean in data science?</h3>
                    <p>Business understanding is like being a consultant who first needs to understand what problem the client actually wants to solve before jumping into any analysis.</p>
                    <p>It involves figuring out exactly what question needs to be answered and what the business really needs, like determining whether a company wants to reduce costs or increase sales.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q14">
                    <h3>How do you measure success in data science projects?</h3>
                    <p>You define success metrics and KPIs upfront - deciding how you'll measure whether your solution actually worked.</p>
                    <p>For example, defining that "success" means increasing customer satisfaction by 10% or reducing delivery time by 2 days.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q15">
                    <h3>What is data acquisition and management?</h3>
                    <p>Data acquisition and management is like being a librarian who needs to find, organize, and maintain all the information required to answer important questions.</p>
                    <p>This includes finding and gathering relevant information from various places, like collecting customer feedback from surveys, social media, and support tickets.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q16">
                    <h3>Why is data governance important?</h3>
                    <p>Data governance ensures the data is accurate, reliable, and properly organized, similar to fact-checking sources and keeping files in order so they can be easily found and trusted.</p>
                    <p>Without it, you can't trust your analysis or conclusions.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q17">
                    <h3>What does "training with labeled data" involve?</h3>
                    <p>Training with labeled data means the computer learns by studying examples where we already know the correct answer, similar to studying for a test with an answer key.</p>
                    <p>The computer uses these labeled examples to learn patterns it can apply to new, unlabeled data.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q18">
                    <h3>How does dimensionality reduction work?</h3>
                    <p>Dimensionality reduction simplifies complex data by finding the most important information and ignoring less important details, like creating a summary of a long book.</p>
                    <p>Google Photos uses this to compress and organize millions of photos by identifying the most important visual features while discarding unnecessary details.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q19">
                    <h3>What is agent-environment interaction?</h3>
                    <p>Agent-environment interaction is like a computer playing a video game where it learns by trying different actions and seeing what happens in response.</p>
                    <p>The "agent" (computer) takes actions in an "environment" and learns from the results.</p>
                </div>
                
                <div class="answer-content" id="q20">
                    <h3>Why should I learn these skills for my career?</h3>
                    <p>As AI continues to reshape industries from healthcare to entertainment, understanding these fields becomes essential for career and business success. Machine learning is your go-to for building smart systems that predict and automate, while data science is your strategic partner for turning overwhelming amounts of information into clear business decisions.</p>
                    <p>The future belongs to professionals who can bridge both worlds - combining machine learning's predictive power with data science's storytelling ability to solve tomorrow's biggest challenges.</p>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
    
    <script>
        function showAnswer() {
            const select = document.getElementById('questionSelect');
            const selectedValue = select.value;
            
            if (!selectedValue) {
                alert('Please select a question first!');
                return;
            }
            
            // Hide default content
            document.getElementById('defaultContent').style.display = 'none';
            
            // Hide all answer contents
            const allAnswers = document.querySelectorAll('.answer-content');
            allAnswers.forEach(answer => {
                answer.classList.remove('active');
            });
            
            // Show selected answer
            const selectedAnswer = document.getElementById(selectedValue);
            if (selectedAnswer) {
                selectedAnswer.classList.add('active');
            }
        }
        
        // Optional: Allow Enter key to submit
        document.getElementById('questionSelect').addEventListener('keypress', function(e) {
            if (e.key === 'Enter') {
                showAnswer();
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
